etymologies: early 19th century. From supra- + spinous, originally after French sus-épineux

definitions: Located above the spine of the scapula; specifically designating a depression in the outer surface of the scapula beneath the spine, especially in "supraspinous fossa".
Located above or dorsal to the spinous processes of the vertebrae; specifically designating a ligament or series of ligaments attached to the tips of the spinous processes of the vertebrae.
